body:
I looked into this and this seems to be the root-cause:
The max_pool2d is exported as an Aten op with ORTModule. The problem is that the default value for the 'stride' parameter is None (https://pytorch.org/docs/stable/generated/torch.nn.MaxPool2d.html#torch.nn.MaxPool2d), which is traced as an UNKNOWN_SCALAR.

graph(%0 : Float(64, 1, 28, 28, strides=[784, 784, 28, 1], requires_grad=0, device=cpu)):
  %1 : Long(2, strides=[1], device=cpu) = onnx::Constant[value= 2  2 [ CPULongType{2} ]]()
  %2 : UNKNOWN_SCALAR(device=cpu) = onnx::Constant[value=[<Tensors>]]()
  %3 : Long(2, strides=[1], device=cpu) = onnx::Constant[value= 0  0 [ CPULongType{2} ]]()
  %4 : Long(2, strides=[1], device=cpu) = onnx::Constant[value= 1  1 [ CPULongType{2} ]]()
  %5 : Long(requires_grad=0, device=cpu) = onnx::Constant[value={0}]()
  %6 : Float(64, 1, 14, 14, strides=[196, 196, 14, 1], requires_grad=0, device=cpu), %7 : Tensor = com.microsoft::ATenOp[name="aten::max_pool2d_with_indices"](%0, %1, %2, %3, %4, %5) # /bert_ort/aibhanda/dspy3.7/lib/python3.7/site-packages/torch/nn/functional.py:659:0

A workaround is to use the torch.nn.MaxPool2D instead, which sets the stride from None to kernel_size correctly (https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/88ed93c2ca0853d7841b3526fb42ca55376438b5/torch/nn/modules/pooling.py#L23) which lets the graph get exported correctly.
